                  "paragraphTitle": "can, could, be able to",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Look at the sentences from What really makes us happy in our jobs? Then complete the rules with can, could or be able to."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 2,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [
                    ""
                  ],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "I only work weekends, so I can study during the week.",
                    "I am able to use all the different skills I learned when I was training.",
                    "In my last job I could choose when I wanted to work.",
                    "I was able to take an extra afternoon off each week."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 3,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [
                    "can, could and be able to: Rules"
                  ],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "We use can and be able to to talk about possibility and ability in the present."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 4,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "We use could and was / were able to to talk about possibility and ability in the past."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 5,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "We usually use be able to or was / were able to for possibilities and abilities at a particular time or for a particular reason."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 6,
                  "paragraphImage": "",
                  "paragraphTitle": "",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "We use be able to immediately before the main verb because can has no -ing form or to + base form."
                  ]
                }
              ],
